<P>In the above pit or &s;haft, which is nearly<NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">A pit has lately been &s;unk at Willington, 5 miles north-ea&s;t from Newca&s;tle, which is 280 yards deep, to the low main coal.</NOTE> the deepe&s;t in the kingdom, there are no le&s;s than 16 &s;eams of coal. But many of the&s;e, from their thinne&s;s, are not workable. The 9th, called the <HI>high main coal,</HI> and the 10th, the <HI>low main coal,</HI> are the two principal &s;eams for affording quan|tities of coal, being together 12&frac12; feet thick, and are tho&s;e mo&s;t generally wrought. But the 10th, 13th, and 14th, are all workable &s;eams, and will afford con&s;iderable quan|tities of coal; the aggregate of the three making nearly 9&frac12; feet thick; &s;o that the total thickne&s;s of the workable &s;eams in this colliery amount to 22 feet.</P>
