<HEAD>ADDENDA.</HEAD>
<P>TO the note, page 68, the reader is de&s;ired to add,&mdash; The re&s;ult of this experiment was, that, in the harve&s;t of 1797, &s;uch parts of the wheat, the &s;eed of which was pickled and limed, as well as that which was pickled and not limed, was nearly free from &s;mut; but that which was neither pickled nor limed, had &s;mutted ears in a|bundance, at lea&s;t a hundred times more than the other: it may be proper to ob&s;erve, the &s;eed was purpo&s;ely taken with a few balls of &s;mut in it.&mdash;This experiment is deci&s;ively in favour of &s;teeping in chamberlye.</P>
<P>The following addition is al&s;o de&s;ired to be made, (at the bottom of page 69.) to the paragraph on drilling, ending, "on moi&s;t &s;oils."&mdash;We have lately found it mo&s;t convenient to yoke two hor&s;es to the drill, one going in each furrow, and to drill &s;even rows upon a ridge, of 80 to 84 inches wide, when the intervals are 10&frac12; or 11 inches; and 90 inches wide, when the intervals are 12 inches.</P>
<P>With the hor&s;es yoked in this manner in a five-row drill, ten rows may be &s;own upon ridges 10&frac34; feet wide, leaving a &s;pace on the top of the ridge, about 14 inches wide, for one of the hor&s;es to travel on; this is &s;uppo&s;ing the intervals 12 inches wide; but, if the intervals be 10&frac12; inches, then the ridges may be 9&frac34; feet wide.&mdash;A light harrow is fixed to the drill, to cover in the &s;eed.</P>
